                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1449" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the service of a pawnbroker- I have some silk stockings and handkerchiefs, pawned on the 23rd of July, for 32s., by a female - I cannot say it was the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-245-person1450">
                  HENRY 
                  FALL
               <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1450" type="surname" value="FALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1450" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1450" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner, and found on her the duplicate of these goods.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-245-person1451">
                  THOMAS 
                  BEIK WALTER
               <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1451" type="surname" value="BEIK WALTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1451" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1451" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. I produce some stockings, and other things, pawned by the prisoner; one lot on the 26th of July, for 3l.; and one lot on the 30th of July, for 5l.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-245-person1452">
                  JAMES 
                  MOTT
               <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1452" type="surname" value="MOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1452" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-person1452" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. I have seven handkerchiefs, and six pairs of silk stockings, pawned by the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. My husband's disgraceful conduct was the cause of my pawning these things - I was privately married to him, but his conduct in going with other females was such that I could not live with him - the man Varley, now in Court, persuaded his son to abscond and leave me destitute; and, on my demanding a maintenance, he promised, on my retiring into Wales, to allow me the vast sum of 20l. a year - I went there; but on my applying to a bank, through which it was to be remitted, he, to my great surprise, refused this 20l. a year, pretending it was not due - my friends then persuaded me to return, and reside near his country seat, till he felt inclined to perform his promise, and send me this handsome settlement of 20l. a year - I went and resided at a little cottage, near his country seat - but finding he would do nothing for me, I went to Mrs. Porter, who let me have the things; but as she had given me twelve months' credit before, I thought I should have time to pay her - I thought, as I had the good had a right to do what I pleased with them - my chief prosecutor would not send me what he promised, though his son got in debt with other women, and it was all laid on my shoulders; and so destitute has my husband left me, that when I go out, I should not know where to turn for a home, nor where to go for a sixpence.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340904-245-verdict1375" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340904-245-verdict1375" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 28. - <rs id="t18340904-245-punish1376" type="punishmentDescription">
